A. Describe a real-world organizational situation or issue in the Data Dictionary you chose, by doing the following:¶

A1. Provide one question that is relevant to your chosen data set. You will answer this question later in the task through an analysis of the cleaned data, using one of the following techniques: chi-square, t-test, or analysis of variance (ANOVA).¶

The Churn Data set consists of 10,000 customers and 50 columns/ variables, some variables showed high correlation with the Churn and can be used for churn probability prediction. The question to be asked is about recognizing which variables have a relationship with the customer's Churn, and to what extent these relationships are reliable and can be used to predict customers churn probability?

A2. Explain how stakeholders in the organization could benefit from an analysis of the data.¶

“Given that it costs 10 times more to acquire a new customer than to retain an existing one, customer retention has now become even more important than customer acquisition. For many providers, retaining highly profitable customers is the number one business goal. To reduce customer churn, telecommunications companies need to predict which customers are at high risk of churn.” (D207 D208 D209 Churn Data Consideration and Dictionary.pdf) In addition to prediction, the company may be interested in finding the main factors that may affect the churn possibility positively and negatively, therefore taking the right actions to deal with those factors. The analysis of the data would give the company and the stakeholders a good idea about these factors and the degree of their reliability.

A3. Identify all of the data in your data set that are relevant to answering your question in part A1¶

The Data are relevant to answering the question in part A1 are the variables that can explain a significant amount of variance in the 'Churn' variable , these variables (or features) can be continuous or categorical variables. One way to identify these variables is by using Statistical Experiments and Significance Testing , which can help (to some extent) in measuring how significantly each variable can explain an amount of variance in 'Churn' , this is related to the degree of correlation between 'Churn' and each of the variables. Correlation technically can measure this amount of variance explaination but only between numweic variables, while Statistical Experiments can find out the Significance for categorical variables. In order to identify all of the data in the data set that are relevant to answering the question in part A1, I have applied different techniques such as correlation , Chi2 testing and Data visualization and it is explained in details in the following sections.

Data visualization:¶

*Function plt_summary() to inspect the data visually usind Histogram, Boxplot and scattered plots. The following function is defined to visually identify statistical parameters and to get the sense from the Data, such as identify the outliers , ranges, dominant values,.etc

In [5]:
'''
Custom function to inspect the data visually using Histogram/Bar, Boxplot and scattered plots
this function takes 2 parameters, 1st is DataFrame , 2nd is the preferable plot ("hist" , "box" , " scat" , "churn_scat" or "churn_histplot" )
For Histograms with non-numeric columns , the function will use Bar charts (in Green color) instead of Histogram
"scat": plotting scatterd plot against the 1st column of the D.F.
"churn_scat": plotting scatterd plot of num. variables against the 'Churn' column of the D.F.
"churn_histplot":plotting histplot of numeric or countplot of cat. variables against the 'Churn' column 
'''

def plt_summary(df_1,plt_type):
    numerics = ['int16', 'int32', 'int64', 'float16', 'float32', 'float64']
    
    if plt_type =='churn_histplot':
        pltlist=df_1.columns
#         for number,cols in enumerate(df_1.columns):
#             if (len(df_1[cols].value_counts())>=20):
#                 pltlist.remove(cols)        
        print("Number of columns:  "+str(len(pltlist))) #Printing the number of columns.
        
    elif plt_type =='hist':
        pltlist=df_1.columns
        print("Number of columns:  "+str(df_1.shape[1])) #Printing the number of columns.
        
    else :
        df_n = df_1.select_dtypes(include=numerics).copy()   # selecting only the numeric columns as it's suitable for mentioned plots
        pltlist=df_n.columns
        print("Number of Numeric columns:  "+str(df_n.shape[1])) #Printing the number of numeric columns.

    
    plt.style.use('default')
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,30))
    plt_rows = 11
    plt_cols = 5
    
    for n, col in enumerate(pltlist):   #enumerating each column of the data, starting from index
        b=n+1
        ax=plt.subplot2grid(shape=(plt_rows,plt_cols),loc=((int(np.ceil(b/plt_cols)-1)),((b-1)%plt_cols)))
        if plt_type == 'hist':
            if df_1[col].dtype in numerics:
                ax.hist(df_1.loc[:,col],bins = 50)  #plotting Histogram
                ax.set_title(str(col)+' (*num)')
            else:
                if len(df_1[col].value_counts())>2000:
                    ax.set_title(str(col)+' ('+str(len(df_1[col].value_counts()))+' unq val.)')
                    continue
                df_1.groupby(col).size().plot.bar(rot=0,color='g') #plotting Bar chart
                ax.set_title(str(col)+' (*categ. '+str(len(df_1[col].value_counts()))+' cat.)')
                if len(df_1[col].value_counts())>20:
                    ax.tick_params(bottom=False,labelbottom=False)
                    
        elif plt_type == 'box':
            msk = ~np.isnan(df_n.loc[:,col])
            ax.boxplot(df_n.loc[msk,col])  #plotting Box plot (used a mask to filter the null values)
            #ax.boxplot(df.loc[:,col])
            ax.set_title(col)
        elif plt_type == 'scat':
            ax.scatter(df_n.iloc[:,0],df_n.loc[:,col],s=0.1,alpha=0.1) #plotting scatterd plot against the 1st column of the D.F.
            ax.set_title(col)
            
        elif plt_type == 'churn_scat':
            ax.scatter(df_n.loc[:,'Churn'],df_n.loc[:,col],s=30,alpha=0.1,color='g') #plotting scatterd plot of num. variables against the 'Churn' column of the D.F.
            ax.set_title(col)
            
        elif plt_type == 'churn_histplot':
            ax.set_title(str(col)+' (*categ. '+str(len(df_1[col].value_counts()))+' cat.)')
            if (len(df_1[col].value_counts())<=700):
                sns.countplot(ax=ax, data = df_1,x = col,hue = 'Churn',alpha=0.7) #plotting countplot of cat. variables against the 'Churn' column
                if len(df_1[col].value_counts())>20:
                    ax.tick_params(bottom=False,labelbottom=False)
#                 for i, p in enumerate(ax.patches):
#                     height = p.get_height()
#                     ax.text(p.get_x()+p.get_width()/2., height + 0.1, height,ha="center")
            elif (df_1[col].dtype in numerics):
                    sns.histplot(df_1, x=col, hue='Churn', element="poly",ax=ax) #plotting histplot of num. variables against the 'Churn' column
                    ax.set_title(str(col)+' (*num)')          
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show() 
   
    return

'''
From text Book "Practical Statistics for Data Scientists: 50+ Essential Concepts Using R and Python"
The associated GitHub code repository 
'''

from matplotlib.collections import EllipseCollection
from matplotlib.colors import Normalize

def plot_corr_ellipses(data, figsize=None, **kwargs):
    ''' https://stackoverflow.com/a/34558488 '''
    M = np.array(data)
    if not M.ndim == 2:
        raise ValueError('data must be a 2D array')
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=figsize, subplot_kw={'aspect':'equal'})
    ax.set_xlim(-0.5, M.shape[1] - 0.5)
    ax.set_ylim(-0.5, M.shape[0] - 0.5)
    ax.invert_yaxis()

    # xy locations of each ellipse center
    xy = np.indices(M.shape)[::-1].reshape(2, -1).T

    # set the relative sizes of the major/minor axes according to the strength of
    # the positive/negative correlation
    w = np.ones_like(M).ravel() + 0.01
    h = 1 - np.abs(M).ravel() - 0.01
    a = 45 * np.sign(M).ravel()

    ec = EllipseCollection(widths=w, heights=h, angles=a, units='x', offsets=xy,
                           norm=Normalize(vmin=-1, vmax=1),
                           transOffset=ax.transData, array=M.ravel(), **kwargs)
    ax.add_collection(ec)

    # if data is a DataFrame, use the row/column names as tick labels
    if isinstance(data, pd.DataFrame):
        ax.set_xticks(np.arange(M.shape[1]))
        ax.set_xticklabels(data.columns, rotation=90)
        ax.tick_params(axis="x", bottom=True, top=True, labelbottom=True, labeltop=True)
        ax.set_yticks(np.arange(M.shape[0]))
        ax.set_yticklabels(data.index)
        ax.grid (True, color = "grey", linewidth = "0.5", linestyle = "-")
    return ec

*Optional - Converting Binary categories into numeric:¶

*Function cat2num() : to convert categorical variables into serial numeric values in integer format

In [9]:
'''
Custom function to convert categorical variables into numeric form.
this function takes 1 parameters, input DataFrame and creates a dectionary for each categorical variable
where dictinary keys are the categogries and the values are serial numeric values
the maximum number of categories this function can handle is 7000
'''
def cat2num(df_1):
    numerics = ['int16', 'int32', 'int64', 'float16', 'float32', 'float64']
    df_num_conv=df_1.copy()
    for n, col in enumerate(df_num_conv.columns):
        if (df_num_conv[col].dtype in numerics) or (len(df_num_conv[col].value_counts())>7000):
            continue
        else:
            cat_dict={y:x for x,y in enumerate(dict(df_raw[col].value_counts()))}
            df_num_conv[col]=df_num_conv[col].replace(cat_dict)
    return df_num_conv

Chi-square implementation¶

*Function chi2_multiple() , apply chi2 test to each variable in dataframe vs. target variable (Churn)

In [12]:
'''
Custom function to apply Chi2 to multiple variables
this function takes 2 parameters, 1st is DataFrame , 2nd is the target variable for Chi2 analysis ('Churn')
The output is a data frame with the Chi2 reults including ('chi2','p-val','dof') for each variable.
'''
def chi2_multiple(df_1,target):
    numerics = ['int16', 'int32', 'int64', 'float16', 'float32', 'float64']
    col_l=[];chi2_l=[];p_l=[];dof_l=[]
    for n,col in enumerate(df_raw.columns):
        #if (not df_raw[col].dtype in numerics) and (len(df_raw[col].value_counts())<2000):
            rows,colms=col,target              
            df_crostab=pd.crosstab(index=df_raw[colms],columns=df_raw[rows],margins = False)
            (chi2,p,dof,_)=stats.chi2_contingency([df_crostab.iloc[x].values for x in range(0,df_crostab.shape[0])])
            col_l.append(col);chi2_l.append(chi2);p_l.append(p);dof_l.append(dof)
    data={'variable':col_l,'chi2':chi2_l,'p-val':p_l,'dof':dof_l}
    df = pd.DataFrame(data=data,columns = ['variable','chi2','p-val','dof'])
    df.set_index('variable',drop=True,inplace= True)
    print('*Chi2 for categorical variables vs. "'+ target+'"')
    return df.sort_values(by='p-val',axis=0,ascending=True)
    #return df.sort_values(by='chi2',axis=0,ascending=False)

B3. Justify why you chose this analysis technique¶

The chi-square test is used with count data to test how well it fits some expected distribution. The most common use of the chi-square statistic in statistical practice is with r × c contingency tables, to assess whether the null hypothesis of independence among variables is reasonable (Bruce et al.,2020).

The null hypothesis assumes that there is no relationship between the tested categorical variable and the "Churn". The alternative hypothesis is that the variation in Churn with the variation in a tested categorical variable is confidently not due to chance.

If the alpha statistics is set to be 0.05 (or confidence 95%), a p-value less than 0.05 means we have enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis at the 95% confidence levels, and accepting the alternative hypothesis, hence the proportions of Churn is dependent (has a relationship with) the groups in the tested categorical variable. (D207:performance lab python - 3.10.1)

E. Summarize the implications of your data analysis by doing the following:¶

E1. Discuss the results of the hypothesis test.¶

The null hypothesis assumes that there is no relationship between the tested categorical variable and the "Churn". The alternative hypothesis is that the variation in Churn with the variation in a tested categorical variable is confidently not due to chance.

If the alpha statistics is set to be 0.05 (or confidence 95%), a p-value less than 0.05 means we have enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis at the 95% confidence levels, and accepting the alternative hypothesis, hence the proportions of Churn is dependent (has a relationship with) the groups in the tested categorical variable. (D207:performance lab python - 3.10.1)

Using the Chi2 test was very beneficial in identifying the categorical features that can explain a significant amount of variance in the 'Churn' variable such as "Contract", "StreamingMovies" , "StreamingTv" ,"Multiple" and "InternetService" by comparing observed vs. expected values.

E2. Discuss the limitations of your data analysis.¶

Using the Chi2 test was very beneficial in identifying the categorical features that can explain a significant amount of variance in the 'Churn' variable such as "Contract" and "StreamingMovies", but it wasn't so successful with the continuous features such as "Bandwidth_GB_Year" and "Tenure", even though both showed considerable correlation with the "Churn" variable. With such continuous variables, the Chi2 test can't determine specific categories to compare observed vs. expected values.

E3. Recommend a course of action based on your results.¶

Both correlation and Chi2 tests showed clear relationships between customers "Churn" probability and several continuous and categorical features from the dataset. continuous variables such as: "Tenure", "Bandwidth_GB_Year" and "MonthlyCharge", in addition to "CaseOrder" (even though it's just an index of the records, but it has an obvious relationship with "Churn") categorical variables such as: "Contract", "StreamingMovies" , "StreamingTv" ,"Multiple" and "InternetService" each feature should be investigated separately and it's easy to recognise the effect of some of them on the customers Churn probability.

For example:

  • "InternetService": Customers with "Fiberoptic" internet service are less likely to churn.
  • "StreamingMovies" and "StreamingTv": Customers with these two services tend to have a high churn probability. , looks like there is a problem with these services.
  • "Bandwidth_GB_Year" : Customers with
  • "MonthlyCharge": Customers with lower monthly charges are less likely to churn.
  • "CaseOrder": Customers with CaseOrder above 5000 are less likely to churn (needs to be interpreted).
  • "Tenure": Old customers with longer Tenure value are less likely to churn, possibly new customers are not enough satisfied.
